<hr data-start="375" data-end="378">
<h3 data-start="380" data-end="416" data-section-id="e4a3mu">🔍 Explanation (Interview Ready)</h3>
<ul data-start="418" data-end="616">
<li data-start="418" data-end="449" data-section-id="164m4iq">
<p data-start="420" data-end="449"><code data-start="420" data-end="423">X</code> → features (input data)</p>
</li>
<li data-start="450" data-end="484" data-section-id="v4l3nu">
<p data-start="452" data-end="484"><code data-start="452" data-end="455">y</code> → target (output variable)</p>
</li>
<li data-start="485" data-end="546" data-section-id="1rkaxry">
<p data-start="487" data-end="546"><code data-start="487" data-end="503">test_size=0.33</code> → 33% data for testing, 67% for training</p>
</li>
<li data-start="547" data-end="616" data-section-id="1c1tw8">
<p data-start="549" data-end="616"><code data-start="549" data-end="566">random_state=42</code> → ensures same split every time (reproducibility)</p>
</li>
</ul>
<hr data-start="618" data-end="621">
<h3 data-start="623" data-end="652" data-section-id="nk1yia">🎯 Short Interview Answer</h3>
<p data-start="654" data-end="792">“I used train_test_split to divide data into training and testing sets with 33% test data. I used random_state to ensure reproducibility.”</p>
<hr data-start="794" data-end="797">
<h3 data-start="799" data-end="813" data-section-id="1ysjva6">🔥 Pro Tip</h3>
<p data-start="815" data-end="829">Common ratios:</p>
<ul data-start="830" data-end="925">
<li data-start="830" data-end="864" data-section-id="peazyx">
<p data-start="832" data-end="864"><code data-start="832" data-end="837">0.2</code> → standard (80-20 split)</p>
</li>
<li data-start="865" data-end="891" data-section-id="1kk3n0i">
<p data-start="867" data-end="891"><code data-start="867" data-end="872">0.3</code> → sometimes used</p>
</li>
<li data-start="892" data-end="925" data-section-id="1d3uf81">
<p data-start="894" data-end="925">Avoid too small training data ❗</p>
</li>
</ul>
